$\begin{align}
&\phantom{=}\dfrac{150{,}000\,\dfrac{\text{views}}{\text{video}}}{15\,\dfrac{\text{minutes}}{\text{video}}}
\\\\
&=\dfrac{150{,}000}{15}\,\dfrac{\text{views}}{\cancel{\text{video}}}\cdot\dfrac{\cancel{\text{videos}}}{\text{minute}}
\\\\
&=10{,}000\,\dfrac{\text{views}}{\text{minute}}
\end{align}$

Now we can plug that in the original equation:

$\begin{align}
0.2\,\dfrac{\text{likes}}{\text{view}}\cdot 10{,}000\,\dfrac{\text{views}}{\text{minute}}&=x\,\dfrac{\text{likes}}{\text{minute}}
\\\\
2000\,\dfrac{\text{likes}}{\text{minute}}&=x\,\dfrac{\text{likes}}{\text{minute}}
\end{align}$

There can be many ways to solve this problem. Here, we will do this by thinking about *units*.

Let's say that last month, Trevor's family spent $x\,\text{dollars}$ on water. We are given that the price of water is $0.20\,\dfrac{\text{dollars}}{\text{liter}}$. How can we relate these two quantities with an equation?

$\begin{align}
y\,\text{liters}\cdot 0.2\,\dfrac{\text{dollars}}{\text{liter}}=x\,\text{dollars}
\end{align}$

So in order to find the total cost $x$, we need to figure out the value of $y$, which is the number of liters of water Trevor's family used.

We can combine the following quantities:

$\begin{align}
6\,\cancel{\text{persons}}\cdot 72\,\dfrac{\text{liters}}{\cancel{\text{person}}}=432\,\text{liters}
\end{align}$

Now we can plug that in the original equation:

$\begin{align}
432\,\text{liters}\cdot 0.2\,\dfrac{\text{dollars}}{\text{liter}}&=x\,\text{dollars}
\\\\
86.4\,\text{dollars}&=x\,\text{dollars}
\end{align}$

There can be many ways to solve this problem. Here, we will do this by thinking about *units*.

